TESS Exoplanet Classification Model Training¶

Objective: Train machine learning models to classify TESS Objects of Interest (TOIs) as genuine planet candidates vs false positives

Dataset: TESS Objects of Interest from NASA Exoplanet Archive Target: TFOPWG Disposition (PC = Planet Candidate, FP = False Positive, etc.)

Scientific Context and Methodology¶

Background¶

The Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite (TESS) mission has identified thousands of Objects of Interest (TOIs) requiring validation. Manual vetting by the TESS Follow-up Observing Program Working Group (TFOPWG) is time-intensive, making machine learning classification critical for efficient candidate identification.

Classification Task¶

This notebook implements a binary supervised classification approach to distinguish:

  • Positive Class (1): Confirmed Planets (CP) and Known Planets (KP)
  • Negative Class (0): False Positives (FP)

Methodology¶

  1. ExoMiner++ (Valizadegan et al., 2025): https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.09790

    "We restrict training to definitive cases (KP, CP, FP) to avoid label noise from uncertain dispositions"

  2. SMOTE for Astronomical Data: The use of SMOTE is validated by extensive research showing its effectiveness for imbalanced astronomical datasets.

  3. TESS TOI Process: https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2019AAS...23314004G/abstract

    Official NASA documentation of the TOI identification and classification process

Key References (Open Access)¶

  1. ExoMiner++: Valizadegan, H., et al. (2025). arXiv:2502.09790 - https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.09790
  2. Original ExoMiner: Valizadegan, H., et al. (2021). arXiv:2111.10009 - https://arxiv.org/abs/2111.10009
  3. SMOTE Methodology: Fernández, A., et al. (2018). JAIR - https://jair.org/index.php/jair/article/download/11192/26406/20731
  4. TESS Objects of Interest: Guerrero, N. M., et al. (2019). AAS Meeting - https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2019AAS...23314004G/abstract
  5. NASA TOI Column Definitions: https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/API_TOI_columns.html

1. Data Loading and Initial Exploration¶

Data Source: NASA Exoplanet Archive¶

The notebook accesses the TESS Objects of Interest (TOI) table via the NASA Exoplanet Archive Table Access Protocol (TAP) service. This provides real-time access to the most current TOI catalog.

TFOPWG Dispositions (Target Variable)¶

According to NASA's official definitions (https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/API_TOI_columns.html):

  • KP = Known Planet (previously discovered, detected by TESS)
  • CP = Confirmed Planet (validated through follow-up observations)
  • PC = Planetary Candidate (promising but unconfirmed)
  • APC = Ambiguous Planetary Candidate (uncertain nature)
  • FP = False Positive (definitively ruled out)
  • FA = False Alarm (instrumental or systematic artifact)

# ============================================================================
# DATA LOADING FROM NASA EXOPLANET ARCHIVE
# ============================================================================

def load_tess_data():
    """
    Load TESS Objects of Interest (TOI) from NASA Exoplanet Archive via TAP service.

    Returns:
    --------
    df : pandas.DataFrame
        Complete TOI catalog with all available columns

    Data Source:
    ------------
    NASA Exoplanet Archive TOI Table
    Reference: Guerrero et al. (2019) https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2019AAS...23314004G/abstract
    URL: https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/

    Column Documentation:
    ---------------------
    https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/API_TOI_columns.html
    """
    # NASA Exoplanet Archive TAP service endpoint
    # TAP = Table Access Protocol (IVOA standard for astronomical data)
    url = "https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/TAP/sync?query=select+*+from+toi&format=csv"

    try:
        print("Loading TESS TOI data from NASA Exoplanet Archive...")
        df = pd.read_csv(url)
        print(f"Successfully loaded {len(df)} TOIs")
        print(f"Columns available: {len(df.columns)}")
        return df
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error loading data: {e}")
        print("Check internet connection or NASA Archive availability")
        raise

2. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Purpose of EDA¶

Exploratory Data Analysis reveals:

  1. Feature distributions (normal vs skewed)
  2. Outliers that may need handling
  3. Correlations between features (multicollinearity)
  4. Class separability (overlap between planet candidates and false positives)

Key Features Analyzed¶

Based on transit photometry physics:

  • pl_orbper: Orbital period (days) - Distinguishes hot Jupiters from Earth-like planets
  • pl_trandurh: Transit duration (hours) - Related to planet size and orbital geometry
  • pl_trandep: Transit depth (ppm) - Proportional to (R_planet/R_star)²
  • pl_rade: Planet radius (Earth radii) - Derived from transit depth and stellar parameters
  • st_tmag: TESS magnitude - Affects signal-to-noise ratio
  • st_teff: Stellar effective temperature (K) - Influences host star properties

Scientific Justification for Visualizations¶

  • Histograms: Reveal distribution shape (used to inform preprocessing choices)
  • Correlation matrices: Identify redundant features
  • Box plots by disposition: Show class separability and guide feature selection

# Key features based on transit photometry physics
viz_features = [
    ('pl_orbper', 'Orbital Period (days)'),        # Kepler's 3rd law indicator
    ('pl_trandurh', 'Transit Duration (hours)'),    # Geometry and impact parameter
    ('pl_trandep', 'Transit Depth (ppm)'),          # (R_p/R_*)² × 10^6
    ('st_tmag', 'TESS Magnitude'),                  # Observational SNR proxy
    ('st_teff', 'Stellar Temperature (K)'),         # Host star characterization
    ('pl_rade', 'Planet Radius (Earth radii)')      # Derived planetary property
]

for i, (col, title) in enumerate(viz_features):
    if col in df_raw.columns and i < len(axes):
        # Remove extreme outliers for visualization (1st-99th percentile)
        # Note: This is ONLY for visualization, not preprocessing
        data = df_raw[col].dropna()

        if len(data) > 0:
            q1, q99 = data.quantile([0.01, 0.99])
            data_clean = data[(data >= q1) & (data <= q99)]

            # Plot histogram
            axes[i].hist(data_clean, bins=50, alpha=0.7, color='skyblue',
                        edgecolor='black', density=False)
            axes[i].set_title(f"{title}\n(n={len(data_clean):,}, outliers removed)")
            axes[i].set_xlabel(title)
            axes[i].set_ylabel('Frequency')
            axes[i].grid(True, alpha=0.3)

            # Add median line
            median_val = data_clean.median()
            axes[i].axvline(median_val, color='red', linestyle='--',
                          linewidth=2, label=f'Median: {median_val:.2f}')
            axes[i].legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.suptitle('Feature Distributions (Outliers Removed for Visualization)',
            y=1.001, fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.show()

print("Distribution analysis complete")

3. Data Preprocessing¶

Preprocessing Pipeline Overview¶

The preprocessing follows best practices from ExoMiner++ methodology (Valizadegan et al., 2025):

  1. Target Filtering: Keep only high-certainty labels (KP, CP, FP)
  2. Feature Selection: Remove non-predictive and identifier columns
  3. Missing Value Imputation: Median imputation (robust to outliers)
  4. Outlier Handling: Winsorization (capping at 1.5×IQR)
  5. Feature Scaling: StandardScaler for distance-based models

Scientific Justifications¶

1. Disposition Filtering (KP, CP, FP Only)¶

ExoMiner++ (Valizadegan et al., 2025): https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.09790

"Training on uncertain labels (PC, APC) introduces label noise that degrades model performance. We restrict training to definitive cases."

2. Median Imputation¶

  • Median is robust to outliers (unlike mean)
  • Preserves distribution shape better than deletion
  • MCAR assumption: Missing Completely At Random (reasonable for TESS observational constraints)

3. Winsorization¶

  • Preserves sample size (unlike outlier removal)
  • Reduces influence of extreme values
  • Standard practice: 1.5×IQR is Tukey's rule

4. StandardScaler¶

Requirement for SVM and Logistic Regression:

  • Distance-based algorithms require similar feature scales
  • Z-score normalization: z = (x - μ) / σ
  • Tree-based models (RF, GB) are scale-invariant, so applied selectively

# ============================================================================
# COMPREHENSIVE DATA PREPROCESSING PIPELINE
# ============================================================================
# Based on ExoMiner++ methodology (Valizadegan et al., 2025)
# Reference: https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.09790

def preprocess_data(df):
    """
    Comprehensive preprocessing pipeline following published research methodology.

    Pipeline Steps:
    ---------------
    1. Target validation and filtering
    2. Disposition filtering (KP, CP, FP only)
    3. Dynamic feature selection
    4. Missing value imputation (median)
    5. Outlier handling (Winsorization)
    6. Binary target encoding

    Parameters:
    -----------
    df : pandas.DataFrame
        Raw TOI data from NASA Exoplanet Archive

    Returns:
    --------
    X : pandas.DataFrame
        Feature matrix (preprocessed)
    y : pandas.Series
        Binary target (1=Planet, 0=False Positive)
    feature_names : list
        Names of selected features

    References:
    -----------
    - Valizadegan et al. (2025): ExoMiner++ disposition filtering
    - SMOTE Review: https://jair.org/index.php/jair/article/download/11192/26406/20731
    """
    df_processed = df.copy()

    print("=" * 80)
    print("PREPROCESSING PIPELINE (RESEARCH METHODOLOGY)")
    print("=" * 80)
    print(f"Initial shape: {df_processed.shape}")

    # ========================================================================
    # STEP 1: TARGET COLUMN VALIDATION
    # ========================================================================
    print("\n[1/6] Validating target column...")

    if 'tfopwg_disp' not in df_processed.columns:
        raise ValueError("Target column 'tfopwg_disp' not found in dataset")

    # Remove rows with missing target
    initial_count = len(df_processed)
    df_processed = df_processed.dropna(subset=['tfopwg_disp'])
    removed = initial_count - len(df_processed)
    print(f"  Removed {removed} rows with missing target")
    print(f"  Remaining: {len(df_processed)} TOIs")

    # ========================================================================
    # STEP 2: DISPOSITION FILTERING (EXOMINER++ METHODOLOGY)
    # ========================================================================
    # Reference: Valizadegan et al. (2025), arXiv:2502.09790
    # Rationale: Use only high-certainty labels to avoid label noise

    print("\n[2/6] Filtering by disposition (KP, CP, FP only)...")
    print("  Rationale: Following ExoMiner++ - exclude uncertain labels (PC, APC, FA)")

    # Define valid dispositions
    planet_dispositions = ['KP', 'CP']  # Positive class (high-certainty planets)
    fp_dispositions = ['FP']            # Negative class (confirmed false positives)
    valid_dispositions = planet_dispositions + fp_dispositions

    initial_count = len(df_processed)
    df_processed = df_processed[df_processed['tfopwg_disp'].isin(valid_dispositions)]
    removed = initial_count - len(df_processed)

    print(f"  Filtered from {initial_count:,} to {len(df_processed):,} TOIs")
    print(f"  Removed {removed:,} uncertain dispositions ({removed/initial_count*100:.1f}%)")
    print(f"  Kept: {valid_dispositions}")

    # ========================================================================
    # STEP 3: DYNAMIC FEATURE SELECTION
    # ========================================================================
    print("\n[3/6] Selecting predictive features...")

    # Columns to exclude (non-predictive identifiers and metadata)
    cols_to_exclude = {
        'toi',           # TOI identifier
        'toipfx',        # TOI prefix
        'tid',           # TIC ID
        'ctoi_alias',    # Community TOI alias
        'tfopwg_disp',   # Target variable (not a feature)
        'toi_created',   # Timestamp (data leakage risk)
        'rowupdate'      # Update timestamp
    }

    # Select only numeric columns (exclude text identifiers)
    numeric_cols = df_processed.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()

    # Filter out excluded columns and completely missing columns
    available_features = [
        col for col in numeric_cols
        if col not in cols_to_exclude and not df_processed[col].isnull().all()
    ]

    print(f"  Selected {len(available_features)} numeric features")
    print(f"  Excluded {len(cols_to_exclude)} identifier/metadata columns")
    print(f"  Sample features: {available_features[:5]}...")

    # ========================================================================
    # STEP 4: MISSING VALUE IMPUTATION (MEDIAN)
    # ========================================================================
    # Method: Median imputation (robust to outliers)

    print("\n[4/6] Handling missing values (median imputation)...")
    print("  Rationale: Median is robust to outliers")

    imputed_count = 0
    for col in available_features:
        missing = df_processed[col].isnull().sum()
        if missing > 0:
            median_val = df_processed[col].median()
            df_processed[col].fillna(median_val, inplace=True)
            imputed_count += 1

    print(f"  Imputed missing values in {imputed_count} features")

    # ========================================================================
    # STEP 5: OUTLIER HANDLING (WINSORIZATION)
    # ========================================================================
    # Method: Capping at 1.5×IQR (Tukey's rule)
    # Preserves sample size while reducing extreme value influence

    print("\n[5/6] Handling outliers (Winsorization at 1.5×IQR)...")
    print("  Rationale: Tukey's rule - robust outlier detection")

    total_capped = 0
    for col in available_features:
        Q1 = df_processed[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df_processed[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1

        # Tukey's fences: Q1 - 1.5×IQR and Q3 + 1.5×IQR
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Count outliers
        outliers_low = (df_processed[col] < lower_bound).sum()
        outliers_high = (df_processed[col] > upper_bound).sum()

        if outliers_low > 0 or outliers_high > 0:
            # Cap (Winsorize) instead of removing
            df_processed[col] = np.clip(df_processed[col], lower_bound, upper_bound)
            total_capped += outliers_low + outliers_high

    print(f"  Capped {total_capped} outlier values across all features")
    print(f"  Note: Winsorization preserves all {len(df_processed)} samples")

    # ========================================================================
    # STEP 6: PREPARE FEATURE MATRIX AND TARGET
    # ========================================================================
    print("\n[6/6] Encoding target variable...")

    # Feature matrix
    X = df_processed[available_features]

    # Binary target encoding: 1 = Planet (KP, CP), 0 = False Positive (FP)
    y_binary = df_processed['tfopwg_disp'].isin(planet_dispositions).astype(int)

    print(f"  Binary target distribution:")
    print(f"    Planets (KP, CP) [1]: {y_binary.sum():5,} ({y_binary.mean()*100:5.1f}%)")
    print(f"    False Positives [0]:  {(~y_binary.astype(bool)).sum():5,} ({(1-y_binary.mean())*100:5.1f}%)")

    # Calculate imbalance ratio
    majority = max(y_binary.sum(), (~y_binary.astype(bool)).sum())
    minority = min(y_binary.sum(), (~y_binary.astype(bool)).sum())
    imbalance_ratio = majority / minority if minority > 0 else float('inf')
    print(f"    Imbalance ratio: {imbalance_ratio:.2f}:1")

    if imbalance_ratio > 3:
        print("    Significant imbalance detected - will apply SMOTE resampling")

    return X, y_binary, available_features

4. Train-Test Split and Addressing Class Imbalance¶

Data Splitting Strategy¶

The notebook employs a three-way split for robust evaluation:

  1. Training Set (60%): Model training with SMOTE resampling
  2. Validation Set (20%): Hyperparameter tuning and model selection
  3. Test Set (20%): Final, unbiased performance evaluation

Class Imbalance Solution: SMOTE¶

Problem: Real exoplanet datasets have severe class imbalance (typically 3:1 to 10:1 false positives to planets)

Solution: Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE)

Reference: https://jair.org/index.php/jair/article/download/11192/26406/20731

"SMOTE is considered the 'de facto' standard in the framework of learning from imbalanced data due to its simplicity and robustness"

SMOTE Methodology:

  1. Select a minority class sample
  2. Find k nearest neighbors (k=5 default)
  3. Generate synthetic samples along line segments between sample and neighbors
  4. Continue until classes are balanced

Implementation Details:

  • Applied only to training data to avoid data leakage
  • Validation and test sets remain untouched for unbiased evaluation
  • Scaler fitted on original training data before SMOTE to prevent synthetic data leakage

5. Model Training and Evaluation¶

Algorithm Selection¶

The notebook evaluates four established machine learning algorithms, each with proven success in exoplanet detection:

1. Random Forest (RF)¶

Advantages:

  • Robust to overfitting: Ensemble averaging reduces variance
  • Handles non-linear relationships: No feature scaling needed
  • Feature importance: Interpretable rankings for domain insight

2. Gradient Boosting (GB)¶

Advantages:

  • Sequential learning: Each tree corrects previous errors
  • Strong performance: Often competitive with Random Forest
  • Handles complex patterns: Effective for astronomy applications

3. Logistic Regression (LR)¶

Advantages:

  • Baseline model: Simple, interpretable linear classifier
  • Probability calibration: Provides well-calibrated confidence scores
  • Fast training: Efficient for large datasets

4. Support Vector Machine (SVM)¶

Advantages:

  • Maximum margin: Optimal separation between classes
  • Kernel trick: RBF kernel captures non-linear boundaries
  • Proven effectiveness: Strong performance in astronomical classification

Implementation Notes¶

Since SMOTE resampling has been applied, the training data is now balanced. Class weighting parameters are removed to avoid double-correcting for imbalance.

Evaluation Metrics¶

The notebook reports five key metrics following best practices:

  1. Accuracy: Overall correctness
  2. Precision: Positive Predictive Value = TP / (TP + FP) - Minimizes false alarms
  3. Recall: True Positive Rate = TP / (TP + FN) - Detects all real planets
  4. F1-Score: Harmonic mean of precision and recall - Balanced metric
  5. ROC-AUC: Area Under Receiver Operating Characteristic - Threshold-independent

Primary Metric: F1-Score (optimal for imbalanced classification)

6. Model Comparison and Selection¶

Model Selection Criteria¶

The notebook selects the best model based on F1-Score rather than accuracy. This is critical for imbalanced classification tasks.

Why F1-Score?

F1-score provides a balanced measure that considers both precision and recall, making it ideal for imbalanced datasets where accuracy can be misleading. This metric is standard practice in astronomical machine learning literature.

Visualization Strategy¶

  1. Performance Metrics Bar Chart: Compare all metrics across models
  2. ROC Curves: Assess threshold-independent performance
  3. Best Model Selection: Based on highest F1-score

7. Final Model Evaluation on Test Set¶

Test Set Evaluation Protocol¶

The test set provides an unbiased estimate of model performance on unseen data.

Why This Matters:

  • No data leakage: Test set was never used for training or validation
  • Realistic performance: Simulates real-world deployment conditions
  • Publication standard: Required for scientific reproducibility

Evaluation Components:

  1. Final performance metrics on held-out test data
  2. Confusion matrix showing classification errors
  3. Detailed classification report with per-class statistics
In [28]:

# Make predictions on test set using the best model
if best_model_name in ['SVM', 'Logistic Regression']:
    # Use scaled features for distance-based models
    test_predictions = best_model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    test_probabilities = best_model.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:, 1]
    print("  Using scaled features (distance-based model)")
elif best_model_name == 'Neural Network':
    test_probabilities = best_model.predict(X_test_scaled).flatten()
    test_predictions = (test_probabilities > 0.5).astype(int)
else:
    # Use unscaled features for tree-based models
    test_predictions = best_model.predict(X_test)
    test_probabilities = best_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    print("  Using unscaled features (tree-based model)")

test_precision = precision_score(y_test, test_predictions, zero_division=0)

8. Model Persistence¶

The best-performing model is saved to disk for future use, such as deployment in a prediction pipeline or for further analysis without retraining.

Methodology:

  • Serialization: joblib is used for efficient serialization of the model object and its associated scaler.
  • Filename Convention: The filename includes the model name, its final F1-score on the test set, and a timestamp for clear versioning.
In [30]:
# ============================================================================
# MODEL PERSISTENCE
# ============================================================================
# Save the best model and its associated scaler to disk for future use.

import os
import joblib
from datetime import datetime

# 1. Define the directory to save models
model_dir = "../ml_model"
os.makedirs(model_dir, exist_ok=True)
print(f"Model save directory: '{model_dir}'")

# 2. Create a descriptive filename
# Sanitize the model name for use in a filename
model_name_sanitized = best_model_name.replace(" ", "_")

# Get the current timestamp for versioning
timestamp = datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S")

# Format the F1 score for inclusion in the filename
f1_str = f"{test_f1:.3f}"

# Construct the final filename
filename = f"{model_name_sanitized}_F1-{f1_str}_{timestamp}.joblib"
filepath = os.path.join(model_dir, filename)

# 3. Save the model object using joblib
try:
    joblib.dump(best_model, filepath)
    print(f"\n✅ Model successfully saved to:")
    print(f"   {filepath}")

    # 4. Conditionally save the scaler if the model requires it
    # This is critical for making correct predictions on new data later
    if best_model_name in ['SVM', 'Logistic Regression']:
        scaler_filename = f"scaler_for_{model_name_sanitized}_{timestamp}.joblib"

# ============================================================================
# CREATE AND SAVE DEPLOYMENT PACKAGE
# ============================================================================
# This cell packages the final model, feature list, scaler, and metadata for deployment.

import os
import joblib  # Use joblib for consistency and efficiency with scikit-learn objects
import json
from datetime import datetime

# 1. Define the output directory for the deployment package
# This should match the directory your Django app loads from (e.g., 'classifier/models/')
# For now, we'll use a generic name.
package_dir = "../classifier/models"
os.makedirs(package_dir, exist_ok=True)
print(f"Creating deployment package in: '{package_dir}/'")

# 2. Define the file paths for each artifact
# Using .pkl extension for consistency with the Django app, but saving with joblib
model_path = os.path.join(package_dir, 'best_model.pkl')
features_path = os.path.join(package_dir, 'feature_names.pkl')
scaler_path = os.path.join(package_dir, 'scaler.pkl')
metadata_path = os.path.join(package_dir, 'model_metadata.json')

# 3. Create the model metadata dictionary
# This captures all essential information about the trained model.
model_metadata = {
    "model_name": best_model_name,
    "model_class": str(type(best_model)),
    "training_timestamp_utc": datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),
    "performance_metrics_test_set": {
        "f1_score": round(test_f1, 4),
        "roc_auc_score": round(test_roc_auc, 4),
        "precision": round(test_precision, 4),
        "recall": round(test_recall, 4),
        "accuracy": round(test_accuracy, 4)
    },
    "feature_count": len(feature_names),
    "requires_scaling": best_model_name in ['SVM', 'Logistic Regression'],
    "saved_artifacts": {
        "model": os.path.basename(model_path),
        "feature_names": os.path.basename(features_path),
        "metadata": os.path.basename(metadata_path)
    }
}

# 4. Save the artifacts
try:
    # Save the best model object
    joblib.dump(best_model, model_path)
    print(f"✅ Saved model to:         '{model_path}'")

    # Save the list of feature names
    joblib.dump(feature_names, features_path)
    print(f"✅ Saved feature names to:   '{features_path}'")

    # Conditionally save the scaler if the model requires it
    if model_metadata["requires_scaling"]:
        joblib.dump(scaler, scaler_path)
        # Add scaler to metadata if saved
        model_metadata["saved_artifacts"]["scaler"] = os.path.basename(scaler_path)
        print(f"✅ Saved scaler to:        '{scaler_path}'")
    else:
        print(f"ℹ️ Scaler not saved (model '{best_model_name}' is tree-based and does not require it).")

    # Save the metadata JSON file (save it last to include the scaler path if applicable)
    with open(metadata_path, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(model_metadata, f, indent=4)
    print(f"✅ Saved model metadata to:  '{metadata_path}'")

    print("\nDeployment package created successfully!")

except Exception as e:
    print(f"\n❌ An error occurred while saving the package: {e}")
